  "text": "[16] We hypothesize that the buoyant force of a fluid reservoir beneath the mainshock hypocenter is causing such an upward flexure of the upper crust. The present study has only indicated localization of fluids just beneath the mainshock hypocenter (Figure 3b ), but regional (larger-scale) tomography [CITATION_1] has suggested that fluids are apparently infiltrating into the seismogenic zone from a deeper and larger fluid reservoir, located at approximately 20 km in depth. A vertical change in the stress state from normal to strike-slip faulting has likewise been reported in the southern Taupo Volcanic Zone in New Zealand, where the seismicity is considered to be related to fluid processes [CITATION_2] .",
